

screen( capsensitive("Editor") )
Editor          (For more information, double-click text in boldface.)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Pure C v1.0 supports up to six edit windows at the same time (or four
edit windows plus the \#Messages\# and \#Help Window\#s).  Later versions
support as many windows as AES allows.

The \#Cut\#, \#Copy\# and \#Paste\# operations can be used to copy text from one
window to another.

These windows support all the standard GEM features: scroll bars,
close icons , resize icons , full size icons , and title (drag)
bars.  The title bar shows the full pathname of the file being edited,
with an '*' to indicate if any edit changes have been made.

Each window is depicted as being 255 characters wide regardless of the
actual content.  (This is also the maximum line length the editor can
handle.)

To open an edit window, see \#File\#/\#Open .C\# through \#Open .PRJ\#
(the editor treats all file types the same).

See also \#Edit\#, \#Search\#, \#edit keys\#, \#block selection\# and
\#block operations\#.
\end

screen( "edit keys" )
Edit Key           | Explanation
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Return             | Create new line, or break line at cursor.
Backspace          | Delete character left of cursor.  If cursor is
                   |  at start of line, merge with previous line.
Delete             | Delete character right of cursor.  If cursor is
                   |  at end of line, merge with next line.
Undo               | Restores the last deleted character, or deletes
                   |  the last entered character.
                   |  Also works on \#block operations\#.
Tab                | Insert TAB character.  Cursor moves to next
                   |  tab stop  (See \#Shell Options\#.)
Home               | Move cursor to top of file.
Shift-Home         | Move cursor to bottom of file.
Up Arrow           | Move cursor to previous line.
Down Arrow         | Move cursor to next line.
Left Arrow         | Move cursor one character left.  If cursor is at
                   |  start of line, move to end of previous line.
Right Arrow        | Move cursor one character right.  If cursor is
                   |  at end of line, move to start of next line.
Shift-Up Arrow     | Move cursor up one page (window height).
Shift-Down Arrow   | Move cursor down one page (window height).
Shift-Left Arrow   | Move cursor to start of line.
Shift-Right Arrow  | Move cursor to end of line.
Control-Left Arrow | Move cursor one word left.
Control-Right Arrow| Move cursor one word right.

See also \#CONTROL\# keys.
\end

screen( "CONTROL" )
Control Codes for Pure C (Editor Commands)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Key(s)       Function
----------------------------------------------------------------------
ESC          View user screen image (\#Edit\#/\#User Screen\#).
SHIFT/SHIFT  Abort compiler.
CONTROL-B    Check for unbalanced braces (\#Search\#/\#Check Braces\#).
CONTROL-C    Copy block to paste buffer (\#Edit\#/\#Copy\#).
CONTROL-D    Print block (\#File\#/\#Print Selection\#).
CONTROL-E    Locate source code which caused the selected error
              message (\#Search\#/\#Find Error\#).
CONTROL-F    Find next occurrence of string (\#Search\#/\#Find...\#).
CONTROL-G    Repeat last search (\#Search\#/\#Find Same\#).
CONTROL-H    Close window, don't save (\#File\#/\#Abandon\#).
CONTROL-I    Find next occurrence of block (\#Search\#/\#Find Selection\#).
CONTROL-J    Remove starting tabs in block (\#Edit\#/\#Shift Left\#).
CONTROL-K    Add starting tabs in block (\#Edit\#/\#Shift Right\#).
CONTROL-L    Locate line by number (\#Search\#/\#Goto Line...\#). 
CONTROL-M    Save under new name (\#File\#/\#Save as...\#).
CONTROL-N    Select entire window (\#Edit\#/\#Select All\#).
CONTROL-O    Open edit window (\#File\#/\#Open .C\#).
CONTROL-P    Print window contents (\#File\#/\#Print\#).
CONTROL-Q    Exit Pure C (\#File\#/\#Quit\#).
CONTROL-R    Locate and replace a string (\#Search\#/\#Replace...\#).
CONTROL-S    Save edit window (\#File\#/\#Save\#).
CONTROL-T    Repeat last replace (\#Search\#/\#Replace Same\#).
CONTROL-U    Close window (\#File\#/\#Close\#).
CONTROL-V    Insert paste buffer contents (\#Edit\#/\#Paste\#).
CONTROL-W    Move bottom window to top (\#Edit\#/\#Cycle Windows\#).
CONTROL-X    Copy block to paste buffer and delete (\#Edit\#/\#Cut\#).
CONTROL-Y    Copy line to paste buffer and delete.

CONTROL/SHIFT-Q  Quit without saving \#Configuration File\#.

See also \#block selection\#, \#edit keys\#, \#Help key\# and \#ALTERNATE\# keys.
\end

screen( "ALTERNATE" )
'Alternate Codes' for Pure C (Project Commands)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Key(s)       Function
----------------------------------------------------------------------
ALTERNATE-A  Assemble (*.S) code in window (\#Compile\#/\#Assemble ''\#)
ALTERNATE-C  Compile (*.C) code in window (\#Compile\#/\#Compile ''\#).
ALTERNATE-D  Make project and execute Pure Debugger
              (\#Project\#/\#Debug ''\#).
ALTERNATE-E  Execute external program (\#Compile\#/\#Execute...\#).
ALTERNATE-F  Search project (\#Search\#/\#Search project...\#).
ALTERNATE-G  Search path (\#Search\#/\#Search multiple...\#).
ALTERNATE-H  Save configuration file (\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\#Save ''\#).
ALTERNATE-I  Set assembler options (\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\#Assembler...\#).
ALTERNATE-J  Load new configuration file (\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\#Load...\#).
ALTERNATE-L  Link project (\#Project\#/\#Link ''\#).
ALTERNATE-M  Make project (\#Project\#/\#Make ''\#).
ALTERNATE-O  Set linker options (\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\#Linker...\#).
ALTERNATE-R  Make project and execute program (\#Project\#/\#Run ''\#).
ALTERNATE-S  Assemble (*.S) file (\#Compile\#/\#Assemble...\#).
ALTERNATE-U  Set compiler options (\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\#Compiler...\#).
ALTERNATE-V  Compile (*.C) file (\#Compile\#/\#Compile...\#).
ALTERNATE-X  Compile all source code files listed in project file
              (\#Project\#/\#Make all ''\#).
ALTERNATE-Z  Set misc. options (\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\#Shell...\#).

ALTERNATE/SHIFT-D Shut down Pure C then start Pure Debugger.

See also \#Project File\# and \#CONTROL\# codes.
\end

screen( "block selection" )
Block Selection
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A selected block of text will appear in reverse video (white letters
on black background).  When a block is selected, the cursor location
is defined as the beginning of the block.

The simplest way to select a block of text is to position the mouse
at either the beginning or end of the block to be selected, drag the
mouse (holding down the left mouse button) to the other end of the
block, then release the mouse button. 

If you drag the mouse past the edge of the active window, the contents
of the window will move to reveal what had been beyond the edge.

One can select everything from the cursor location to the mouse
pointer by pressing the 'Shift' key while clicking the mouse.

One can select the entire contents of a window using the
\#Edit\#/\#Select All\# command or pressing \#CONTROL\#-N.

One can select a word by double clicking it with the mouse.

One can select everything between a '( )' pair, a '[ ]' pair, or a
'{ }' pair by double clicking one of the two parenthesis, brackets
or braces (respectively).

\#Search\# operations leave a block selected if they are successful.
\#Find Error\# and \#Goto Line...\# select a whole line.

See also \#block operations\#.
\end

screen( "block operations" )
block operations
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... use the paste buffer to move text blocks from one location to
another within a window or between windows.  All operations which
write to the paste buffer destroy its previous contents.

\#Cut\# \#CONTROL\#-X or 'Delete' copies the selected block to the paste
buffer and deletes it from the window.

\#CONTROL\#-Y copies the current line to the paste buffer and deletes
it from the window.

\#Copy\# or \#CONTROL\#-C copies the selected block to the paste buffer.

\#Paste\# or \#CONTROL\#-V or 'Insert' inserts the paste buffer contents
at the cursor location.

'Backspace' deletes the selected block.

'Undo' un-does the last block (or character) operation.

\#Shift Left\# or \#CONTROL\#-J removes a tab from the start of each line
within the selected block (or the equivalent number of spaces).

\#Shift Right\# or \#CONTROL\#-K adds a tab to the start of each line
within the selected block.

\#Print Selection\# or \#CONTROL\#-D prints the block.

\#Find Selection\# or \#CONTROL\#-I locates the next occurrence of the
block (and selects it).

See also \#block selection\#.
\end

screen( "File Selector" )
File Selector
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The small window displays a list of folders and files (which match the
current extension) found in the current folder.  The selected file or
folder is shown in reverse video (white letters on black background).
One can select a file or folder by clicking it with the mouse, or by
using the  and  keys and pressing RETURN, or by typing in the name.

Double clicking a file name will 'Open' the file (see below).
Double clicking a folder name will display its contents.

Clicking the '' (close icon) will back up to the parent folder.

One can select a new drive by clicking a button on the left
(labelled 'A:', 'B:', etc.).

One can change the extension by clicking a button in the middle
(labelled '*.*', '*.C', etc.).

'Open'       displays the selected folder or uses the selected file
             for the calling function.

'New'        creates an new file to be used for the calling function.
             Another dialog box will appear to enter the new name.

'Cancel'     returns without perform the calling function.

Calling functions include \#Open .C\#, \#Print\#, \#Save as...\#, \#Compile...\#,
\#Assemble...\#, \#Execute...\#, \#Select...\#, and \#Load...\#

The remaining buttons have nothing to do with the calling function:

'New Folder' creates a new folder within the current folder.
'Delete'     deletes the selected file.
'Touch'      changes the file's creation time/date to the current
              time/date.  (See also \#Make ''\#.)
'Copy'       copies the file.  Another dialog box will appear to
              enter the new file name.  (Will not change folders.)
'Info'       displays the size, date, time, and write protection
              status of a file.  One can also use this button to
              rename the file or change its status.
\end

screen( "*.PRJ",
		capsensitive("Project File") )
Project File  (*.PRJ)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The project file is used by the \#Project\# commands to define which files
need to be compiled, assembled and/or linked together to create an
executable program.

Since even the most simple programs require a certain amount of
linking, a project file is always needed to run a program.  The
provided file DEFAULT.PRJ will run a program if its source code is
entirely contained in the active edit window.

Project files have the following \#syntax\#:

  { <output_file> | * }
  { .L [ \#Linker Options\# ] }
  { .C [ \#Compiler Options\# ] }
  { .S [ \#Assembler Options\# ] }
  =
  <module_name1> { [ <options> ] }  { ( <include_files> ) }
  <module_name2> { [ <options> ] }  { ( <include_files> ) }
  ...

The <output_file> should have either a .TOS .TTP .PRG .ACC or .LIB
extension. See \#Program Extensions\#.

Each <module_name> can either be an asterisk '*', to represent the
active edit window, a source code filename, an object filename, a
library filename, or an included project filename.  These modules will
be linked in the order they appear, so the startup module \link("%%GLOBAL%%")PCSTART\#.O
\link("%%GLOBAL%%")PCXSTART\#.O or \link("%%GLOBAL%%")PCVSTART\#.O must go first and the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Libraries\# usually
go last.

The <options> list refers to \#Compiler Options\# or \#Assembler Options\#,
and only applies to source code files.  (These lists can be used to
set flags which are clear by default, but not to clear flags which
are set by default.)

The <include_files> list forces the module to be re-compiled if any
of the listed files is changed.

See also \#Project Examples\# and \#Linker\#.
\end

screen( "syntax" )
Syntax
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Items in angle-brackets '< >' are variable.
Items in braces '{ }' are optional.
A bar '|' denotes a choice between two options.
Blanks don't count.
\end

screen( "Project Examples" )
Examples of Project Files
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Example 1:

hello.tos      ;no graphics interface
=
PCSTART.O
hello.c
PCSTDLIB.LIB


  Example 2:

math.lib       ;not executable
.L [-J]        ;create library file
.C [-2 -8]     ;use 68030 and 68881 processors
=
conjgrad.c (math.h)
simplex.c (math.h)
eigen.c (math.h)


  Example 3:

;uses resource file 'test.rsc' with header 'test.h'
;math.h and math.lib are in another folder

test.prg
.C [-8]
.L [-G -L -Y]   ;debugging plotter.c
= 
PCSTART.O
main.c (plotter.h test.h ..\\math\\math.h)
plotter.c [-Y] (plotter.h)
..\\math\\math.lib
PC881LIB.LIB    ;-8 option affects parameter passing
PCSTDLIB.LIB    ;must be after PC881LIB or PCFLTLIB
PCGEMLIB.LIB
PCTOSLIB.LIB
\end

screen( "Configuration File",
		"*.CFG" )
Configuration File  (*.CFG)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The configuration file contains essentially everything about the
current status of PC.PRG, including the settings for all of the
\link("Options Menu")Options\#, which edit windows are open, where they are open, the
\#Search Options\#, the \#Find...\# and \#Replace...\# strings, and even
the arguments used for \#Execute...\#

File PC.CFG is loaded automatically when PC.PRG is started, and can be
saved automatically when PC.PRG is terminated by setting the autosave
flag of the \#Shell Options\#.

\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\#Save ''\# will save the configuration file on request.

\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\#Load...\# can be used to load a different configuration file,
and/or change the filename used for subsequent saves.
\end

screen( "Project Database",
		"Project Help",
		"*.PDB" )
Project Help  (*.PDB)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
By setting the Project Help flag of the \#Shell Options\#, Pure C will
create a Project Database file which can be used to locate the source
code definitions for data structures, constants, variables and
functions (even when the code is found in another file).

Simply place with cursor within the name in question and press the
\#Help key\#.  (If the name in question is also a context sensitive Help
keyword, Project Help takes precedence.  If you want the Help entry,
either turn off Project Help or search through the Index.)

Pressing the UNDO key will return you to your previous location.

The name of the *.PDB file used/created is the same as the *.PRJ file.
(See also \#Project\#/\#Select...\#)
\end

screen( "Help Window" )
Help Window
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The help window can be initiated using the drop-down \#Help\# menu or by
pressing the \#Help key\# while the cursor is within a context sensitive
keyword.

Within the text of help window are keywords in boldface and
underlined.  By double clicking the mouse on a keyword, or by
placing the cursor within a keyword and pressing the \#Help key\#,
a different help window will appear with additional information.

To return to the previous help window, press the UNDO key.

To close the help window, press \#CONTROL\#-U or click the  (close icon)
in the upper left-hand corner of the window.

You can create your own help windows using the \#Help Compiler\# to
create a \#USR.HLP\# file.
\end

screen( "Help key" )
Help key
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The 'Help' key can be used to select a keyword within a help window,
or bring up a help window without going through the drop-down \#Help\#
menu, or locate the definition of a data structure, constant, variable
or function using \#Project Help\#.

If you are editing a file and the cursor is within a context sensitive
help keyword when the 'Help' key is pressed, the \#Help Window\# for that
keyword will appear directly.  (Note, not all keywords shown in the
\#Index\# are context sensitive.)

One can create additional context sensitive keywords by using the
\#Help Compiler\# to create a \#USR.HLP\# file.

If nothing is selected when the 'Help' key is pressed, the \#Index\#
help window will appear.

If the \#Project Help\# option is set, when a data structure, constant,
variable or function is selected and the 'Help' key is pressed, the
source code definition for that item will be found (even if it is in
another file).

See also \#Shell Options\#.
\end

screen( "Search Options" )
Search Options
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\#Backwards\#
\#Ignore Case\#
\#All\#
\#Whole Word\#
\#List only first occurence\#
\#Search subdirectories\#

See also \#Find...\# and \#Replace...\#
\end

screen( "Backwards" )
Backwards
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Search through the active window for the PREVIOUS occurrence of a text
string (starting from the cursor location).

Note: This direction is reversed each time a search fails (unless the
      \#All\# option is selected).

See also \#Find...\# and \#Replace...\#
\end

screen( "Ignore Case" )
Ignore Case
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Ignore the case of any of the characters in the text string being
located.  For example 'TEXT' 'text' or even 'TeXt' would all be
treated as equivalent.

See also \#Find...\#, \#Replace...\#, \#Search project...\# and \#Search multiple...\#
\end

screen( "All" )
All
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Replace every occurrence of the selected string starting from the
cursor position in the direction specified by the \#Backwards\# option.

See also \#Replace...\#
\end

screen( "Whole Word" )
Whole Word
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The string being located must be preceded and followed by word
termination characters, such as Tab Space Comma Period ( ) [ ] { }
' " + - * / = & | ! ^ ~ < > ? : ; % \\ or Newline.
Characters _ and # will not work.

For example, searching for 'test' will find ' test ' and '(test)' but
not 'testify', 'test2' or 'error_test'.

See also \#Find...\#, \#Replace...\#, \#Search project...\# and \#Search multiple...\#
\end

screen( "List only first occurence" )
List only first occurence
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... searches every file, but only lists the first match in each file
in the \#Messages\# window.

See also \#Search project...\# and \#Search multiple...\#
\end

screen( "Search subdirectories" )
Search subdirectories
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... not only searches every file (matching the wildcards) in the
specified directory, but also files in any subdirectories of the
specified directory, and any subdirectories of the subdirectories,
and so on (i.e., the entire subdirectory tree).

See also \#Search multiple...\#
\end

screen( "Messages" )
Messages Window
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The 'Messages' window is automatically opened by the compiler,
assembler or linker to display \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Compiler Errors\#, \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Warning\#s,
\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Assembler Errors\# or \#Linker Errors\#.

It is also used by the \#Search project...\# and \#Search multiple...\#
commands to list matches.

By double-clicking a compiler error or warning message (or using the
\#Search\#/\#Find Error\# command), the source code which caused the error
(or at least the line which was being processed when the error was
noticed) will be located.  (See also \#Search\#/\#Check Braces\#.)

Note: If you add or remove a source code line while fixing one error,
      subsequent error messages will no longer be correctly aligned
      with the source code.

When you \#Close\# the Messages window, its contents are erased.
\end

screen( "Resource File",
		"*.RSC" )
Resource File  (*.RSC)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A resource file defines drop-down menus, dialog boxes, icons, and
other image and text data used in the Application Environment Services
(AES) of a GEM program.

A resource file editor allows a programmer to create a graphical user
interface in WYSIWYG fashion by placing, dragging, resizing, cutting
and pasting the various \link("%%GLOBAL%%")OBJECT\#s on the screen with the mouse.  It
will generally also produce a C language header file containing macro
definitions for named indexes to be used by \link("%%GLOBAL%%")rsrc_gaddr\#().

Additional information available under \link("%%GLOBAL%%")RSHDR\#.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Error") )
Error Messages
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Compiler Errors\#

\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Assembler Errors\#

\#Linker Errors\#

\#Help Compiler Messages\#

See also PASM \link("%%GLOBAL%%")ERROR\# directive.
\end

