screen( "Open .C" )
\#File\#/Open .C                                                 \#CONTROL\#-O
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... uses the \#File Selector\# with the '.C' extension set to open
a C language source code file for editing.

Note: one can change the extension inside the \#File Selector\#.
\end

screen( "Open .H" )
\#File\#/Open .H
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... uses the \#File Selector\# with the '.H' extension set to open a
C language header file for editing.
\end

screen( "Open .S" )
\#File\#/Open .S
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... uses the \#File Selector\# with the '.S' extension set to open an
assembly language source code file for editing.
\end

screen( "Open .PRJ" )
\#File\#/Open .PRJ
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... uses the \#File Selector\# with the '.PRJ' extension set to open a
\#Project File\# for editing.

See also \#Project\#/\#Select...\#
\end

screen( "Print" )
\#File\#/Print                                                   \#CONTROL\#-P
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... prints the contents of the active window.  This works for \#Messages\#
and \#Help Window\#s as well as edit windows.
\end

screen( "Print Selection" )
\#File\#/Print Selection                                         \#CONTROL\#-D
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... prints the selected text block (if any) in the active window.

See also \#block selection\#.
\end

screen( "Close" )
\#File\#/Close                                                   \#CONTROL\#-U
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... closes the active window.  If there have been editing changes,
will ask whether you wish to save the file first.

Equivalent to clicking the close window icon '' (upper left corner).
\end

screen( "Abandon" )
\#File\#/Abandon                                                 \#CONTROL\#-H
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... closes the active window without saving the file.
\end

screen( "Save" )
\#File\#/Save                                                    \#CONTROL\#-S
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... saves the file in the active window using the filename shown in
the window title bar.  ('*' indicates editing changes.)
\end

screen( "Save as..." )
\#File\#/Save as...                                              \#CONTROL\#-M
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... uses the \#File Selector\# to save the file in the active window
under a new filename.  The window will also be renamed.
\end

screen( "TOS Shell" )
\#File\#/TOS Shell                                               \#CONTROL\#-Z
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
... activates a user supplied subshell routine (if any).

The system variable _shell_p ($4F6) must contain the address of the
routine, or environment parameter SHELL must define a pathname.
\end

screen( "Quit" )
\#File\#/Quit                                 SHIFT-\#CONTROL\#-Q or \#CONTROL\#-Q
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... closes all windows and terminates Pure C.  Asks whether edit
changes are to be saved first.

The SHIFT-\#CONTROL\#-Q key combination, or holding down the SHIFT key
while clicking 'Quit' will terminate Pure C without saving the
\#Configuration File\#.

See also the autosave feature of the \#Shell Options\#.
\end

screen( "Undo" )
\#Edit\#/Undo                                                         UNDO
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... undoes the last edit operation.

For example, a text block which had been \#Cut\# will be restored, or a
text block which had been \#Paste\#d will be removed.  A single character
which had been removed using DELETE or BACKSPACE will be restored, or
a single character which had been typed will be removed.  A second
UNDO will restore the text to its condition before the first UNDO.
\end

screen( "Cut" )
\#Edit\#/Cut                                                     \#CONTROL\#-X
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... deletes the selected block of text from the active window.  This
block can then be copied (usually at a different location) using the
\#Paste\# command.

See also \#block selection\#.
\end

screen( "Copy" )
\#Edit\#/Copy                                                    \#CONTROL\#-C
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... prepares a selected block of text to be copied using the \#Paste\#
command.  Unlike \#Cut\#, Copy does not delete the original block.

See also \#block selection\#.
\end

screen( "Paste" )
\#Edit\#/Paste                                         INSERT or \#CONTROL\#-V
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... inserts the block of text last processed by \#Cut\# or \#Copy\# into
the active window at the cursor location.  Multiple copies can be
generated by repeating the paste command.  One can copy from one
window and paste into another.

If another block of text is selected when the paste command is used,
the new block will be replaced by the block to be pasted.

See also \#block selection\#.
\end

screen( "Select All" )
\#Edit\#/Select All                                              \#CONTROL\#-H
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... selects the entire contents of the active window as a text block.
This is useful to insert the contents of one file into another.

See also \#Cut\#, \#Copy\#, \#Paste\# and \#block selection\#.
\end

screen( "Shift Left" )
\#Edit\#/Shift Left                                              \#CONTROL\#-J                  
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... deletes a TAB (or eqivalent number of SPACEs) from the start of
every line in the selected block of text.

See also \#Shift Right\# and \#block selection\#.
\end

screen( "Shift Right" )
\#Edit\#/Shift Right                                             \#CONTROL\#-K
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... inserts a TAB at the start of every line in the selected block of
text.

See also \#Shift Left\# and \#block selection\#.
\end

screen( "Cycle Windows" )
\#Edit\#/Cycle Windows                                           \#CONTROL\#-W
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... moves the bottom-most window to the top, making it the active
window.

One can also swap windows by clicking the mouse on any exposed section
of a partially obscured window, moving it to the top.
\end

screen( "User Screen" )
\#Edit\#/User Screen                                                   ESC
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... shows the screen image corresponding to the last \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Execute\# or \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Run\#
command.  (Pure C maintains two screen images in memory.)

One can return to Pure C by pressing any key.
\end

screen( "Find..." )
\#Search\#/Find...                                               \#CONTROL\#-F
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... locates the next occurrence of a text string starting from the
current cursor location.  This command opens a dialog box where one
can specify the string to be found and select search options
\#Backwards\#, \#Ignore Case\#, and/or \#Whole Word\#.
\end

screen( "Find Same" )
\#Search\#/Find Same                                             \#CONTROL\#-G
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... locates the next occurrence of a text string starting from the
current cursor location, using the string last specified by either
\#Search\#/\#Find...\# or \#Search\#/\#Find Selection\# and the search options last
specified by \#Search\#/\#Find...\#

Note: the search direction is reversed each time a search fails.
\end

screen( "Find Selection" )
\#Search\#/Find Selection                                         \#CONTROL\#-T
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... locates the next occurrence of a selected block of text using the
search options last specified by \#Search\#/\#Find...\#

Note: the search direction is reversed each time a search fails.

See also \#block selection\#.
\end

screen( "Replace..." )
\#Search\#/Replace...                                            \#CONTROL\#-R
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... locates and replaces one text string with another.  This command
opens a dialog box where one can specify the string to be located,
the string to replace it, and the search options \#Backwards\#,
\#Ignore Case\#, \#All\# and/or \#Whole Word\#.
\end

screen( "Replace Same" )
\#Search\#/Replace Same                                          \#CONTROL\#-T
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... locates and replaces the next occurrence of a text string using
the strings and options last specified by \#Search\#/\#Replace...\#

Note: the search direction is reversed each time a search fails
      (unless the \#All\# option is selected).
\end

screen( capsensitive("Check Braces") )
\#Search\#/Check Braces                                          \#CONTROL\#-B
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... checks the active window for unbalanced braces, '{' and '}', and
locates the first offending brace (if any).  This command is available
only when editing *.C source code.

Note: double-clicking a brace will select the entire block of text
      between it and its corresponding end brace.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Find Error") )
\#Search\#/Find Error                                            \#CONTROL\#-E
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... locates the source code line corresponding to the warning or error
message selected in the \#Messages\# window (where the cursor is located).

A faster method is to double click the error message.
\end

screen( capsensitive("Goto Line...") )
\#Search\#/Goto Line...                                          \#CONTROL\#-L
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... locates a particular line by its line number. A dialog box is used
to enter the desired line number.

Since the default line number is the current cursor location, this
command can also be used as a 'Goto Cursor' or 'Goto start of block'
command.
\end

screen( "Search project..." )
\#Search\#/Search project...                                   \#ALTERNATE\#-F
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... searches all the source and header files listed in the currrent
\#Project File\# for a text string.  This command opens a dialog box where
one can enter the text to be located and select search options
\#Whole Word\#, \#Ignore Case\# and \#List only first occurence\#.

The \#Messages\# window will list all of the matches found.  Double
clicking a line in this window will open an edit window showing the
line containing the match.

See also \#Project\#/\#Select...\#
\end

screen( "Search multiple..." )
\#Search\#/Search multiple...                                  \#ALTERNATE\#-G
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... searches all files which match the directory\\filename (wildcards)
specification for a text string.  This command opens a dialog box
where one can enter the text to be located, the directory pathname and
filename, and specify search options \#Whole Word\#, \#Ignore Case\#,
\#List only first occurence\# and \#Search subdirectories\#.

The filename specification can include wildcards '?' and '*':

  Search for: size_t
  Directory:  C:\\PC\\INCLUDE
  Filename:   *.h

The \#Messages\# window will list all of the matches found.  Double
clicking a line in this window will open an edit window showing the
line containing the match.
\end

screen( "Compile..." )
\#Compile\#/Compile...                                         \#ALTERNATE\#-V
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... compiles a C source code file, using the \#File Selector\# to select
the file to be compiled.

Error messages will appear in the \#Messages\# window.

See also \#Compiler Options\#, \#Find Error\# and \#Project\#.
\end

screen( "Compile ''" )
\#Compile\#/Compile ''                                         \#ALTERNATE\#-C
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... compiles the C source code in the active window (as opposed to the
saved version).

Error messages will appear in the \#Messages\# window.

See also \#Compiler Options\#, \#Find Error\# and \#Project\#.
\end

screen( "Assemble..." )
\#Compile\#/Assemble...                                        \#ALTERNATE\#-S
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... compiles an assembly language source code file, using the
\#File Selector\# to select the file to be compiled.

Error messages will appear in the \#Messages\# window.

See also \#Assembler Options\#, \#Find Error\# and \#Project\#.
\end

screen( "Assemble ''" )
\#Compile\#/Assemble ''                                        \#ALTERNATE\#-A
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... compiles the assembly language source code in the active window
(as opposed to the saved version).

Error messages will appear in the \#Messages\# window.

See also \#Assembler Options\#, \#Find Error\# and \#Project\#.
\end

screen( "Execute..." )
\#Compile\#/Execute...                                         \#ALTERNATE\#-E
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... loads and starts an executable (linked) program, using the
\#File Selector\# to select the program to be executed.

This command is particularly useful for executing utilities such as
the \#Help Compiler\# or a \#Resource File\# editor.

See also \#Project\#/\#Run ''\# and \#Edit\#/\#User Screen\#.
\end

screen( "Select..." )
\#Project\#/Select...                                          \#ALTERNATE\#-P
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... selects a \#Project File\# using the \#File Selector\#.

Note: DEFAULT.PRJ can be used to link a program which has its source
      code entirely contained in the active window (not counting
      \link("%%GLOBAL%%")#include\#s).

See also \#Project Help\#.
\end

screen( "Debug ''" )
\#Project\#/Debug ''                      SHIFT-\#ALTERNATE\#-D or \#ALTERNATE\#-D
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... compiles and links all updated source files specified in the
\#Project File\#, then starts the Pure Debugger (PD.PRG).

Note: one must set the -Y \#Compiler Options\# and the -GLY \#Linker Options\#
      to debug in source code format.  (Actually, one need set the -Y
      option only for those modules where the problem is suspected.)

Using the SHIFT-\#ALTERNATE\#-D key combination or pressing the SHIFT key
while clicking \#Project\#/Debug '' with the mouse will remove Pure C from
RAM before loading the Pure Debugger.  One will return to Pure C after
quitting Pure Debugger.  (You might want to set the \#Configuration File\#
autosave option first.  See \#Shell Options\#.)
\end

screen( capsensitive("Run ''") )
\#Project\#/Run ''                                             \#ALTERNATE\#-R
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... compiles and links all updated source files specified in the
\#Project File\#, then loads and executes the program.

Note: 'Run' compares the date/time of each source file and its object
       file to see if it needs to be re-compiled.  It also compares
       the date/time of the linked file to the object files to see if
       they need to be re-linked.

See also \#Edit\#/\#User Screen\#.
\end

screen( "Make ''" )
\#Project\#/Make ''                                            \#ALTERNATE\#-M
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... compiles and links all updated source files specified in the
\#Project File\#.

Note: 'Make' compares the date/time of the source file and its object
      file to see if it needs to be re-compiled.  It also compares the
      date/time of the linked file to the object files to see if they
      need to be re-linked.
\end

screen( "Make all ''" )
\#Project\#/Make all ''                                        \#ALTERNATE\#-X
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... compiles and links all files specified in the \#Project File\#.

If the \#Compiler Options\# are changed, one can use 'Make All' to
force all of the files to be re-compiled.
\end

screen( "Link ''" )
\#Project\#/Link ''                                            \#ALTERNATE\#-L
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... links the files specified in the \#Project File\#.

If the \#Linker Options\# are changed, one can use 'Link' to force the
files to be re-linked.
\end

screen( "Shell...",
		capsensitive("Shell Options") )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/Shell                                              \#ALTERNATE\#-Z
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Windows:    \#Auto indent\#       \#Use Clipboard\#
\#Autosave\#:   Configuation      Files
Project:    \#Project Help\#      \#Auto dependencies\#
Filebox:    \#Standard file selector\#

Tabsize - Enter the number of columns between tab stops.

Break make on warnings of compiler and/or linker - Normally the \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Make\#
        process breaks on error messages and ignores warnings.

Cache - The cache is used to reduce disk I/O by storing files in RAM.
        Header files refer to all files read using \link("%%GLOBAL%%")#include\#.  Object
        files are created by the compiler and used by the linker.
        Clearing the cache writes the files to disk (if modified) and
        frees the RAM for use by the program to be run.
\end

screen( "Auto indent" )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Shell\#/Auto indent
----------------------------------------------------------------------
When you create a new line by typing RETURN, the number of starting
TABs in the current line will be copied to the new line and the cursor
will be placed after them.
\end

screen( "Use Clipboard" )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Shell\#/Use Clipboard
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The clipboard can be used to copy text from one program to another in
a multitasking environment.  The text to be copied will be written to
disk file in the scrap directory (e.g. C:\\CLIPBRD\\SCRAP.TXT).

See also \link("%%GLOBAL%%")scrp_read\# and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")scrp_write\#.
\end

screen( "Autosave" )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Shell\#/Autosave
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... automatically saves the \#Configuration File\# and/or all files being
edited before running a program.

If there is any possibility of the program crashing, use autosave!
Otherwise all your changes may be lost.
\end

screen( "Auto dependencies" )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Shell\#/Auto dependencies
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The \#Project File\# normally lists all included files (dependencies) with
each source file, e.g.:

  main.c (rsc.h)

The \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Make\# process will recompile the source file (main.c) if any of the
dependencies (rsc.h) have been modified, even if the source file is
unchanged.

The Auto dependencies option will search the source file for all
\link("%%GLOBAL%%")#include\# directives and use these files instead.  (The dependencies
in the \#Project File\# will be ignored.)
\end

screen( "Standard file selector" )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Shell\#/Standard file selector
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... replaces Pure C's \#File Selector\# with the default file selector
(e.g., UIS if installed).
\end

screen( "Compiler...",
		capsensitive("Compiler Options") )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/Compiler...                                        \#ALTERNATE\#-U
----------------------------------------------------------------------
-A  Generate errors on non-ANSI keywords, like \link("%%GLOBAL%%")cdecl\# or \link("%%GLOBAL%%")pascal\#.
-C  Allow nested comments; e.g. /* /* */ */ is a valid comment.
-Y  Add debug information.  See \#Debug ''\#.
-T  Generate run-time error if insufficient stack space has been
    reserved.
-B  Write object files in DRI format for use with another linker.
    (The Pure Debugger will not work with DRI format objects.)
-X  Add an underbar to the beginning of global names.
    (For compatibility with Mark Williams C.)
-H  Pass all function arguments on the stack.  See also \link("%%GLOBAL%%")cdecl\#.
-Q  Use \link("%%GLOBAL%%")pascal\# parameter passing. 
-K  Default \link("%%GLOBAL%%")char\# data type is \link("%%GLOBAL%%")unsigned\# (0-256).
-J  Do NOT rearrange code to reduce jumps.
-Z  Do NOT try to keep repeatedly accessed values in registers.
-M  Do NOT merge string definitions together.
-R  Do NOT implement \link("%%GLOBAL%%")register\# variables on registers.
-G  Optimize program size (instead of execution speed).
-P  Use absolute addressing for external functions.
    Fixes \#Linker PC overflow\# error.
-S  Use \link("%%GLOBAL%%")LINK\# and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")UNLK\# instructions to manipulate stack pointer
    (used to allocate local variables in stack).
-2  Use expanded 68020 instruction set.
-8  Use 68881 floating point coprocessor (12 byte \link("%%GLOBAL%%")double\#).
    One must link \link("%%GLOBAL%%")PC881LIB\#.LIB instead of \link("%%GLOBAL%%")PCFLTLIB\#.LIB.
    (See \#Project File\# and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Parameter Passing\#.)
    This only works for 68881 or 68882 FPU's, not the SFP004.

Include directory:  (-N option)
    Pathname for directory containing Pure C header files;
    e.g. 'include' or 'd:\\pc\\include'

Output directory:  (-O option)
    Pathname for directory to contain object files (*.O).
    Default is to use the same directory as source code.

Define macro:  (-D option)
    'xxx' or 'xxx=yyy' equivalent to '#define xxx' or
    '#define xxx yyy' (respectively) in source code.
    (Usually used for conditional compilation;
    e.g. '#ifdef xxx' or '#if xxx == yyy' directives.)

Stop after ___ errors  (-E option)  See also \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Compiler Errors\#.

Stop after ___ warnings  (-F option)  See also \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Warning\#.

Maximum identifier length ___  (-L option)
    Applies to variables, functions, and macro names, etc.
    Enter number between 1 and 255.

Warning level (0..2) _  (-W option)
    0 - Report no warning messages.
    1 - Report some warning messages.
    2 - Report all warning messages.
    (See also \link("%%GLOBAL%%")#pragma warn\#.)
\end

screen( "Assembler...",
		capsensitive("Assembler Options") )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/Assembler...                                       \#ALTERNATE\#-I
----------------------------------------------------------------------
-1  Use 68010 instructions; e.g. \link("%%GLOBAL%%")MOVE\# from SR & \link("%%GLOBAL%%")MOVEC\#
-2  Use 68020 instructions and addressing modes; e.g. \link("%%GLOBAL%%")DIVSL\#,
    \link("%%GLOBAL%%")DIVUL\# & \link("%%GLOBAL%%")TRAPcc\#
-3  Use 68030 instructions and addressing modes.
-4  Use 68040 instructions and addressing modes.
-5  Use 68851 memory manager instructions; e.g. \link("%%GLOBAL%%")CALLM\# & \link("%%GLOBAL%%")RTM\#
-8  Use 68881 floating point processor instructions.
-S  Use supervisor mode instructions.
-Y  Store information for Pure Debugger.
-B  Create DRI format object files for use with another linker.
    (The Pure Debugger will not work with DRI format objects.)
-C  Do not list lines from included files.
-F  Do not list lines excluded by IF/ELSE/ENDIF directives.
-M  Do not list macro definitions.
-A  List macro expansions.
-P  Produce a listing (creates file *.LST).
-U  Assume all undefined labels are external.
-V  Verbose messages.

Include directory:  (-I option)
    Directory containing include files.
    Defaults to source directory.

Define macro:  (-D option)
    'xxx=yyy' equivalent to 'xxx = yyy' in source code.

Output directory:  (-O option)
    Directory to contain object file (*.O)
    Defaults to source directory.
\end

screen( "Linker...",
		capsensitive("Linker Options") )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/Linker...                                          \#ALTERNATE\#-O
----------------------------------------------------------------------
-G  Add global symbols to symbol table.   (See \#Debug ''\#).
-L  Add local symbols to symbol table.  (See \#Debug ''\#).
-Y  Add debug information.  (See \#Debug ''\#).
-J  Create library file instead of executable program.
-F  Do not set Fastload bit.  Fastload (available starting with
    TOS 1.4) does not zero out the heap space.
-R  Load program to \link("%%GLOBAL%%")ST RAM\# (applies only to TT and Falcon).
-M  Allocate memory from \link("%%GLOBAL%%")ST RAM\# (applies only to TT and Falcon).
-V  Generate verbose messages (symbol table listing, etc).

Stacksize:  (-S option)
    Size of RAM allocated to stack (default is 4096 bytes).
    (See also -T flag from \#Compiler Options\# and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")PCSTART\#.)

Heapsize:  (-H option)
    Sets the TPAsize field (applies only to TT and Falcon).
    If the program is to be loaded into \link("%%GLOBAL%%")TT RAM\# and there is more
    \link("%%GLOBAL%%")ST RAM\# than \link("%%GLOBAL%%")TT RAM\#, then unless there will be at least
    'heapsize' Kbytes of free \link("%%GLOBAL%%")TT RAM\# after the program is loaded,
    load the program into \link("%%GLOBAL%%")ST RAM\#.
    (TPAsize increments in units of 128 Kbytes.)

PLINK can also be used to generate non-relocatable code.
(Not a good idea unless you are trying to program a ROM!)
The following allow you to set the absolute starting addresses for
the program. 

Text segment address:  (-T option)
Data segment address:  (-D option)
BSS segment address:   (-B option)

See also \#Linker\#.
\end

screen( "Load..." )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/Load...                                            \#ALTERNATE\#-J
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... uses the \#File Selector\# to load a previously saved
\#Configuration File\#, or create a new \#Configuration File\# with a
different filename.

Subsequent saves will use the new filename.

File PC.CFG is loaded automatically when Pure C starts.
\end

screen( "Save ''" )
\link("Options Menu")Options\#/Save ''                                            \#ALTERNATE\#-H
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... saves the current version of the \#Configuration File\#.

See also Autosave/Configuration flag from \#Shell Options\#.
\end

screen( "Options Help",
		capsensitive("Options") )
Options Help    (For more information, double-click text in boldface.)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\#Shell Options\#         - Windows, Autosave, Project Help, Cache
\#Compiler Options\#      - Arguments for PCC.TTP and CCP.TTP
\#Assembler Options\#     - Arguments for PASM.TTP
\#Linker Options\#        - Arguments for PLINK.TTP

\#Search Options\#        - Backwards, Ignore Case, Whole Word, etc.
\#Help Compiler Options\# - Arguments for HC.TTP

See also \#Options Menu\#.
\end

screen( "Index Help" )
Index Help
----------------------------------------------------------------------
        Pure C           - PC.HLP
        C Language       - C.HLP
        Libraries        - LIB.HLP
        Assembler        - PASM.HLP
        Userdefined Help - \#USR.HLP\#

The index contains the list of all keywords for each of the help
files.

Keywords are arranged in alphabetical order and grouped by their
first letter.
\end

screen( "Linker",
		capsensitive("PLINK"),
		capsensitive("_StkSize") )
Linker
----------------------------------------------------------------------
... combines the text, data and BSS segments from several object files
and resolves all global name references.  It reserves space in the BSS
segment for the stack and defines global name _StkSize (which IS the
stack size, not the address of a variable containing the stack size).

Its output can be either an executable program or a library file.
(Only those subsegments needed will be linked into an executable
program.)

    \#Program Extensions\#
    \#Program Segments\#
    \#Object File Format\#
    \#Executable File Format\#
    \#Absolute File Format\#
    \#Linker Errors\#

See Also: \link("%%GLOBAL%%")PCSTART\# and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Libraries\#.
\end

screen( "Program Extensions" )
Program Extensions
----------------------------------------------------------------------
TOS  Used for programs which perform terminal I/O using 'standard I/O'
     functions, such as \link("%%GLOBAL%%")puts\# and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Cconws\#.  See \#User Screen\#.

TTP  Same as TOS except that the operating system will allow you to
     enter a UNIX style command line.  See \link("%%GLOBAL%%")main\#.

PRG  Used for programs which perform terminal I/O using \link("%%GLOBAL%%")AES\# and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")VDI\#
     graphics.  Also used for programs in the \#AUTO folder\#.

ACC  Used for accessories.  Accessories residing on the boot disk are
     loaded automatically by GEMDOS at boot time and whenever the
     resolution is changed.  They install themselves on the leftmost
     drop-down menu using \link("%%GLOBAL%%")menu_register\# then wait for a \link("%%GLOBAL%%")MN_SELECTED\#
     event using \link("%%GLOBAL%%")evnt_mesag\# or \link("%%GLOBAL%%")evnt_multi\#.

LIB  Used for libraries (see the -J flag from \#Linker Options\#).
     Libraries are simply an object file formed by linking several
     object files together (used to reduce the number of entries in
     the \#Project File\#).
\end

screen( "AUTO folder" )
AUTO Folder
----------------------------------------------------------------------
During the boot process, all programs with a PRG extension which are
located in the AUTO folder will be executed before any accessories are
loaded or the desktop starts.

They will be executed in the order in which they appear in the
directory.  To change this order, one can move all the files out of
the AUTO folder then move them back in the desired order.  There are
also programs (such as AUTOSORT) which can perform this function.

In most versions of TOS, AUTO programs cannot use \link("%%GLOBAL%%")AES\# or \link("%%GLOBAL%%")VDI\# graphics.

See also \link("%%GLOBAL%%")_p_cookies\#.
\end

screen( "Program Segments" )
Program Segments
----------------------------------------------------------------------
A program is loaded into memory in the following form:

  \link("%%GLOBAL%%")BASPAG\#       - basepage (256 bytes)
  text segment - program instructions
  data segment - constants and initialized variables
  BSS segment  - un-initialized variables
  stack        - all remaining contiguous RAM

Note: \link("%%GLOBAL%%")PCSTART\# reduces the stack and releases excess RAM to the
      heap (see \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Malloc\# and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")malloc\#).
\end

screen( "Object File Format" )
Object File Format
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  \#oheader\#         - 32 bytes
  text segment    - program instructions
  data segment    - constants and initialized variables
  \#relocation code\# - used to link symbols with program
  symbol table    - Pascal strings (first byte = length)
  debug info

The header contains the size of each section.

Note: PLINK also supports DRI format object files (produced by other
      compilers).
\end

screen( "oheader" )
Object File Header Format
----------------------------------------------------------------------
struct oheader {
  int magic;      /* magic number 0x4efa  */
  int hsize;      /* length of remaining header = 28 */
  long psize;     /* size of text + data segments */
  long rsize;     /* size of relocation code */
  long ssize;     /* size of symbol table */
  long reserved1; /* must be zero */
  long dbsize;    /* size of debug info */
  long reserved2; /* must be zero */
  long reserved3; /* must be zero */
 };
\end

screen( "relocation code" )
Relocation Code
----------------------------------------------------------------------
struct reloc {
  unsigned char code;    /* type of operation */
  unsigned char offset;  /* offset from last definition */
  int           symbol;  /* index into symbol table, or -1 */
 };

Partial List of Codes:

  1 - end of code (text + data + BSS).
  2 - skip offset + (symbol * 256) bytes.
  3 - start of text subsegment.
  4 - start of data subsegment.
  5 - start of BSS subsegment.
  6 - end of library.
  7 - define word aligned global address.
  8 - define general global address.
  9 - define word aligned local address.
 10 - define general local address.
 11 - relocate absolute.
 14 - relocate PC relative.

To relate 'symbol' to the text in symbol table, create a pointer array
for the strings and use 'symbol' as the array index.
\end

screen( "Executable File Format" )
Executable File Format
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  \#drihdr\#               - 28 bytes
  text segment         - program instructions
  data segment         - constants and initialized variables
  \#symbol table\#         - not used by loader
  first fixup location - 4 bytes (0L means no fixups needed)
  fixup codes          - 1 byte each, null terminated
  debug info           - not used by loader

The loader simply adds the address of the start of the text segment
to every long word which needs a fixup.  The fixup codes are:

     0 - end of fixup codes
     1 - skip 254 bytes
 2-254 - (even) offset to next fixup
 3-255 - (odd) undefined
\end

screen( "drihdr" )
Program Header Format
----------------------------------------------------------------------
struct drihdr {
  int magic;      /* magic number 0x601a          */
  long tsize;     /* size of text segment         */
  long dsize;     /* size of data segment         */
  long bsize;     /* size of BSS segment          */
  long ssize;     /* size of symbol table         */
  long reserved1; /* must be zero                 */
  long flags;     /* bit flags for fastload, etc. */
  int  absflag;   /* must be zero                 */
 };

When absflag is not zero, it indicates that there is no fixup code.
However, early versions of TOS do not honor this.
\end

screen( "symbol table" )
DRI Symbol Table Format
----------------------------------------------------------------------
struct table {
  char name[8];        /* NULL padded - max 8 characters    */
  unsigned int flags;  /* bit flags                         */
  long addr;           /* location of symbol reference      */
 };

The bit flags are:

0x8000  Label definition
0x4000  Equated label
0x2000  Global label
0x1000  Register equate
0x0800  External label
0x0400  addr = offset from start of TEXT segment
0x0200  addr = offset from start of DATA segment
0x0100  addr = offset from start of BSS segment
\end

screen( "Absolute File Format" )
Absolute File Format
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  \#abshdr\#               - 36 bytes
  text segment         - program instructions
  data segment         - constants and initialized variables
  \#symbol table\#         - not used by loader
  first fixup location - 4 bytes (0L means no fixups needed).
  fixup codes          - 1 byte each, null terminated
  debug info           - not used by loader

The loader simply adds the address of the start of the text segment
to every long word which needs a fixup.  The fixup codes are:

     0 - end of fixup codes
     1 - skip 254 bytes
 2-254 - (even) offset to next fixup
 3-255 - (odd) undefined

Same as the \#Executable File Format\# except for the header.
\end

screen( "abshdr" )
Absolute File Header Format
----------------------------------------------------------------------
struct abshdr {
  int magic;      /* magic number 0x601b  */
  long tsize;     /* size of text segment */
  long dsize;     /* size of data segment */
  long bsize;     /* size of BSS segment */
  long ssize;     /* size of symbol table */
  long reserved;  /* must be zero */
  long textbase;  /* load address for text segment */
  long relocflag; /* zero if fixup code needed */
  long database;  /* load address for data segment */
  long bssbase;   /* load address for BSS segment */
 };
\end

screen( "Linker Errors" )
Linker Error Messages                          (in alphabetical order)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
        (For more information, double click the [?] button.)

\link("Linker PC overflow")[?]\#  16 bit PC relative overflow: 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker 16 bit relocation")[?]\#  16 bit relocation is not supported 
\link("Linker input error")[?]\#  Cannot close file 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker output error")[?]\#  Cannot create file 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker input error")[?]\#  Cannot open file 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker duplicate error")[?]\#  Doubly defined symbol: 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker format error")[?]\#  Format error in object file 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker option error")[?]\#  Illegal option set
\link("Linker option error")[?]\#  Missing argument in option 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker format error")[?]\#  Neither text nor data in input files
\link("Linker RAM error")[?]\#  Not enough memory
\link("Linker input error")[?]\#  Read error on file 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker output error")[?]\#  Seek error on file 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker undefined symbol")[?]\#  Undefined symbol: 'XXXXXX'
\link("Linker unknown error")[?]\#  Unknown error: #
\link("Linker unknown error")[?]\#  Unknown fatal error: #
\link("Linker user break")[?]\#  User break: Linker aborted
\link("Linker output error")[?]\#  Write error on file 'XXXXXX'
\end

screen( "Linker output error" )
\#Linker\# Output Errors
----------------------------------------------------------------------
An I/O error occurred while writing the program to disk.

Check for write protection, free disk space, bad sectors or (rarely)
directory full.
\end

screen( "Linker input error" )
\#Linker\# Input Errors
----------------------------------------------------------------------
An I/O error occurred while reading an object file.

Check for bad sectors, re-compile object file or restore library from
backup.
\end

screen( "Linker PC overflow" )
\#Linker\# PC Relative Overflow Error
----------------------------------------------------------------------
\link("%%GLOBAL%%")BSR\# and other PC relative instructions can only access addresses
ņ32 Kbytes and the address is located further away than that.

Re-compile setting the -P flag from \#Compiler Options\# and/or replace
\link("%%GLOBAL%%")BSR\# with \link("%%GLOBAL%%")JSR\# in assembly code (for global functions).
\end

screen( "Linker 16 bit relocation" )
\#Linker\# 16 bit relocation is not supported 
----------------------------------------------------------------------
DRI object file created by some other compiler used 16 bit relocation.
PLINK does not support 16 bit relocation.
\end

screen( "Linker duplicate error" )
\#Linker\# Doubly defined symbol: 'XXXXXX'
----------------------------------------------------------------------
XXXXXX was used in two different function definitions, two different
global variable definitions, or as both a function and a global
variable name.  (Actually, it could be more than two.)

If the definitions are identical, simply delete one of them.

Otherwise you must either make one (or both) of the definitions \link("%%GLOBAL%%")static\#
or rename one of the functions (or global variables) and all of its
references.
\end

screen( "Linker RAM error" )
\#Linker\# Not enough memory
----------------------------------------------------------------------
First, turn off and clear the cache using \#Shell Options\#.
Second, turn off -Y flags from \#Compiler Options\# and \#Assembler Options\#.
Third, remove all accessories and/or boot programs.

If that doesn't work, either write smaller programs or get a bigger
computer. 
\end

screen( "Linker undefined symbol" )
\#Linker\# Undefined symbol: 'XXXXXX'
----------------------------------------------------------------------
XXXXXX was referenced as external but was never defined.

Check your \#Project File\# to see if all the needed \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Libraries\#
or modules are being linked.
\end

screen( "Linker unknown error" )
\#Linker\# Unknown error: #
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Note down error number and call Gribnif to complain.
\end

screen( "Linker user break" )
\#Linker\# User Break
----------------------------------------------------------------------
You used the 'SHIFT/SHIFT' abort key combination.
\end

screen( "Linker option error" )
\#Linker\# Options Error
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Somehow PC.PRG constructed a bad command line for PLINK.TTP

Check the edit fields in \#Linker Options\# for blanks or commas.
\end

screen( "Linker format error" )
\#Linker\# Format Error
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Object file does not have a valid format.  (See \#Object File Format\#.)  

Re-compile or restore from backup.
\end

screen( "USR.HLP" )
Userdefined Help
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Pure C will look for help keywords in a file by the name of USR.HLP
which can be created using the \#Help Compiler\#.

Context sensitive keywords can be triggered from an edit window using
the help key.  The keyword \link("%%GLOBAL%%")User Help\# is reserved for use by USR.HLP,
so that it can be accessed from the \#Menu\# screen.

One can also intercept calls to the context sensitive keywords already
defined in PC.HLP, C.HLP, LIB.HLP, and PASM.HLP.  The \#Help\# drop-down
menu uses the context sensitive keywords \#Menu\#, \#Editor\#, \link("%%GLOBAL%%")C Language\#,
\link("%%GLOBAL%%")Libraries\#, \#Options\# and \link("%%GLOBAL%%")Assembler\# which can be intercepted.

Once you are in a help window from USR.HLP, you can only return to a
help window in one of the other help files by using a context
sensitive keyword defined in the other file.

Note: Context sensitive keywords containing blanks cannot be accessed
      using the HELP key.
\end

screen( "Help Compiler" )
Help Compiler
----------------------------------------------------------------------
HC.TTP can be used to create your own help files, such as \#USR.HLP\#.
Its only argument is the filename of the command file, which must be
in the following \#syntax\#:

-<options>
USR.HLP
<source_file_1>
<source_file_2>
...

See \#Help Compiler Options\# for the list of options.  (The '-' is
required even if no options are specified.)

See \#Help Compiler Language\# for a description of the source code.

See \#Help Compiler Messages\# for a list or error and warning
messages generated by the help compiler.

Note: the \#Index\# is generated automatically.
\end

screen( "Help Compiler Options" )
\#Help Compiler\# Options
----------------------------------------------------------------------
L    Produce log file HC.LOG (copy of output to \#User Screen\#).
N    Parse source file, but do not generate help file.
T=n  Translate TABs as "n" blanks, where 0 < n < 10.  Default is 4.
     (Does not use tab stops.)
V    Verbose message output.
W    Break on warning.
G=n  Adjust texts in index pages for lang x
     Currently supported:
     G=0 english texts
     G=1 german texts

0    Create new PC.HLP or PD.HLP file.
1    Create new C.HLP file.
2    Create new LIB.HLP file.
3    Create new PASM.HLP file.
4    Create USR.HLP file (default).

Here is a sample command file:

-LVT=8     ;log file on, verbose output, tab size = 8
USR.HLP    ;Help file name
USR.TXT    ;Source file
\end

screen( capsensitive("Help Compiler Language") )
Help Compiler Language
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The source files for the help compiler contain blocks of separated
text, where each block defines one \#Help Window\# screen.
The \#syntax\# of each block follows:

screen(\link("Help Compiler - keywords")<keywords>\#)
<several lines of help window text>
\\end

The text of the help window will appear almost verbatim.
The exceptions to this are:

TAB key  Expanded according to the \#Help Compiler Options\#.
\\\\       Translated as a single \\.
\\EOF     Translated as ''.

\\#       Used to mark the beginning and end of an external keyword.
         \\#keyword\\# will appear as \#keyword\#.

\\link    Alias the shown text as another keyword.
         \\link("keyword")alias\\# will appear as \link("keyword")alias\#
         but will pull up the 'keyword' screen.

\\print   Write message to screen: \\print("This text is written.")

\\extern  No function; used as a comment.  Also \\0 through \\9.


Example: The following two help screens are linked together:

    screen("First")
    Double-click the underlined text to go to the \\#Second\\# screen.
    \\end

    screen("Second")
    Double-click \\link("First")here\\# to return.
    \\end

Note: 'here' will not appear in the Index.

Also, the '\\link' command cannot be used to alias a keyword which is
a context sensitive keyword from another help file.
\end

screen( "Help Compiler - keywords",
		capsensitive("capsensitive"),
		capsensitive("sensitive") )
Help Compiler - keywords
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The 'screen( )' command argument list consists are one or more
keyword definition separated by commas and/or blanks.  Each keyword
definition can be of the \link("syntax")form\#:

  "<keyword>"
  sensitive("<keyword>")
  capsensitive("<keyword>")

The 'sensitive( )' and 'capsensitive( )' functions are used to define
context sensitive keywords.  While ordinary help keywords can be used
to link help screens together, context dependent keywords can also be
used to bring up a help screen from an edit window by pressing the
\#Help key\#, or to link screens from different help files.

Keywords defined by 'sensitive( )' can be either upper or lower case,
or any combination thereof, so that 'sensitive("text")' would respond
to 'text', 'TEXT' or even 'TeXt'.  They will appear in the \#Index\# in
upper case.

Keywords defined by 'capsensitive( )' must match exactly.

All keywords defined by a 'screen( )' command will appear in the
\#Index\#, as opposed to aliases used by the \\link( ) \\# command.

Keywords 'Version', 'Index', 'A..' through 'Z..', and 'Other'
are generated by HC.TTP (after patch) and cannot be redefined.

PC.PRG uses context sensitive keywords 'Menu', 'Editor', 'C Language',
'Libraries', 'Options' and 'Assembler' to implement the \#Help\# drop-down
menu.  These CAN be redefined and intercepted by \#USR.HLP\#
\end

screen( "keyword" )
screen("keyword")
Included simply to demonstrate the \#Help Compiler Language\#.
Press UNDO key to return.
\end

screen( "Help Compiler Messages" )
Error and Warning Messages from the Help Compiler
----------------------------------------------------------------------
    (For more information, double-click the [?] button.)

\link("HC tab error")[?]\#  '=' expected in option
\link("HC duplicate name")[?]\#  Doubly defined screen name
\link("HC option error")[?]\#  Illegal option character
\link("HC missing end")[?]\#  Missing end of screen
\link("HC missing parameter")[?]\#  Missing Parameter
\link("HC out of RAM")[?]\#  Out of memory
\link("HC missing quote")[?]\#  Pending end of string
\link("HC input error")[?]\#  Read error
\link("HC unknown screen")[?]\#  Reference to unknown screen
\link("HC screen to long")[?]\#  Screen too long
\link("HC link error")[?]\#  Too many parameters
\link("HC too many files")[?]\#  Too many source file in command file
\link("HC output error")[?]\#  Unable to open output file
\link("HC input error")[?]\#  Unable to open command file
\link("HC input error")[?]\#  Unable to open source file
\link("HC unknown statement")[?]\#  Unknown statement
\link("HC bad character")[?]\#  Use of illegal character
\link("HC output error")[?]\#  Write error
\link("HC bad parameter")[?]\#  Wrong parameter type
\link("HC wrong scope")[?]\#  Wrong scope for statement
\end

screen( "HC unknown screen" )
Warning: Reference to unknown screen
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  A keyword was used which was not defined in a screen keyword list.

  This message is always given when referencing context keywords from
  another help file.
\end

screen( "HC missing parameter" )
Warning: Missing Parameter
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  No keyword definition was found between two commas in a screen()
  keyword list.
\end

screen( "HC tab error" )
Error: '=' expected in option
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  The 'T' option was entered in the command file with no '=nn'.
  (See \#Help Compiler Options\#.)
\end

screen( "HC duplicate name" )
Error: Doubly defined screen name
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  A screen keyword has been used already for another screen.
\end

screen( "HC option error" )
Error: Illegal option character
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Legal options are L, N, T, V, W and 0-4.
  (See \#Help Compiler Options\#.)
\end

screen( "HC missing end" )
Error: Missing end of screen
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  No '\\end' found before end of source file.
\end

screen( "HC missing quote" )
Error: Pending end of string
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  No closing " before end of line.
\end

screen( "HC screen to long" )
Error: Screen too long
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Each screen can be at most 32 Kbytes.  (Check for missing '\\end'.)
\end

screen( "HC link error" )
Error: Too many parameters
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  The \\link( ) function can only contain one string inside its
  parenthesis.
\end

screen( "HC too many files" )
Error: Too many source file in command file
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  At most 64 source files can be used.
\end

screen( "HC unknown statement" )
Error: Unknown statement
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Something was found before a 'screen( )' and/or after an '\\end'.
\end

screen( "HC bad character" )
Error: Use of illegal character
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  '\\x1d' cannot be used in a source file.
\end

screen( "HC bad parameter" )
Error: Wrong parameter type
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  All parameters must be strings in quotes " ".
\end

screen( "HC wrong scope" )
Error: Wrong scope for statement
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  '\\link' '\\#' or '\\end' was found before a 'screen( )' and/or after
  an '\\end' statement.
\end

screen( "HC out of RAM" )
Error: Out of memory
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Execute HC.TTP from the desktop.
  Remove accessories and boot files.
  Get a bigger computer.
\end

screen( "HC input error" )
Help Compiler Input File Error
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Check for missing file, missing folder or bad sectors.
\end

screen( "HC output error" )
Help Compiler Output File Error
----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Check for write protection, missing folder, disk full or (rarely)
  directory full.
\end

